web_results.snippet: The bluefish is the only extant species of the family Pomatomidae. It is a marine pelagic fish found around the world in temperate and subtropical waters, except for the northern Pacific Ocean. Bluefish are known as tailor in Australia and New Zealand, elf and shad in South Africa.

buttons.subtitle: Are Bluefish Good To Eat?
buttons.title: Maine Seafood Guide - Bluefish - Maine Sea Grant
buttons.snippet: Bluefish is best eaten as fresh as possible, as it tends to degrade over time and doesn't keep or freeze well. It has a delicate flavor but can be more “fishy” than other types of seafood. Marinate or cook in acidic liquids to minimize fishiness. Bluefish is soft, and is best grilled, baked, broiled, or smoked.
snippet_highlighted_words: Bluefish is best eaten as fresh as possible, as it tends to degrade over time and doesn't keep or freeze well

buttons.subtitle: What Does Bluefish Taste Like
buttons.title: Bluefish - Locals Seafood
buttons.snippet: Bluefish has a bad reputation as having a “fishy” taste. When handled incorrectly, the rich flavor of bluefish will get even richer. Here at Locals, we love the flavor of fresh bluefish and take great care to handle it properly. Our fish is cut at the last minute and kept extremely cold until it hits your bag.

buttons.subtitle: Are Bluefish Aggressive
buttons.title: Bluefish - Delaware Fish Facts for The Recreational Angler
buttons.snippet: Bluefish are so aggressive they have bitten human swimmers who were unfortunate enough to encounter a feeding school. Bluefish are well known to anglers as an incredible fighter with tremendous power. When Bluefish are in a feeding frenzy, they will strike almost any object in front of them.

buttons.subtitle: Bluefish Age
buttons.title: Bluefish | NOAA Fisheries
buttons.snippet: Bluefish live up to 12 years. They grow fast, up to 31 pounds and 39 inches. They are able to reproduce at age 2, when they're 15 to 20 inches in length. Depending on their size, females can have between 400,000 and 2 million eggs.

buttons.subtitle: What Do Bluefish Eat?
buttons.title: Learn about bluefish - Mass.gov
buttons.snippet: They are voracious predators and can be seen feeding at the surface on schools of bait fish. Bluefish eat plankton when they are young, but transition to a piscivorous diet as they get older. Early in life bluefish are hunted by larger fish such as: Striped bass.
snippet_highlighted_words: plankton when they are young, but transition to a piscivorous diet as they get older

buttons.subtitle: Bluefish Name Ideas
buttons.title: Fish Profile - New York Sea Grant
buttons.snippet: Local names used for bluefish include: “snapper” or “snap mackerel” (10 inch fish), “blue” or “cocktail blue” (2 lb fish), and “gorilla gator” (15-20 lb fish). Their strong biting power makes them an excellent sport fish, especially for those anglers who enjoy fishing in a blitz.
